column11: To invoke Article 50 of the Treaty of Lisbon a member state must notify the European Council of its intention to withdraw from the European Union (Washington Post, Lisbon Treaty). Although a majority of voters in the United Kingdom's June 2016 referendum on European Union membership voted to leave the EU (BBC), it is unclear when Article 50 will be invoked or if it will govern the UK's withdrawal process (Wall Street Journal, Reuters, Financial Times). Recommended Questions Before 1 July 2017, will Scotland set a date for another referendum on independence from the United Kingdom? Before 1 July 2017, will any other European Union (EU) member state set a date for a referendum on leaving the EU? What will the end-of-day closing value for the British pound against the US dollar be on 30 December 2016? This question was closed as "Between 1 January 2017 and 30 June 2017" with an end date of 29 March 2017 (Reuters, CNN, BBC). As the phoney war draws to a close, swords are being sharpened on both sides of the English Channel for the genuine fights ahead. Soon Theresa May, Britain’s prime minister, will invoke Article 50 of the European Union treaty, beginning a two-year negotiation over Britain’s departure. An early battle will be over the Brexit tab, made up largely of outstanding budgetary commitments and pension liabilities: the European Commission may demand up to €60bn ($64bn). Having done nothing to prepare British opinion for an exit charge, Mrs May can expect outrage from Britain’s slavering tabloids and restive MPs; that may limit her negotiating room. Expect a scrap, too, on the sequence of events. British negotiators want to open talks on a post-Brexit settlement, including a trade deal, before the terms of departure have been agreed upon—issues that Michel Barnier, the commission’s Brexit negotiator, wants to keep separate. The divorce will be messy

The House of Lords could plausibly cause delays - but the overwhelming support for triggering Article 50 in the Commons, combined with the conclusive referendum result, means that doing so would be likely to have substantial political costs: i.e its abolition or radical (and it must be said overdue) reform. When it comes to the real constitutional balance of powers the Lords has a weak hand that it will not overplay. The new support for Brexit is the latest case of the old story of the British Establishment absorbing those it formerly opposed (the anti-EU "bastards") and essentially accepting their arguments. For the first time in decades the Conservative Party is united over Europe - while Labour is split. The Lib Dem Peers will try to delay as much as they can - but their party's marginal representation in the Commons now means they don't really have a leg to stand on. While the party that actually has been providing substantive opposition in the Commons - the Scots Nats - don't have any Lords.... It should go through as planned by May.

Recent interviews with Mrs May indicate that she has a clear idea of what she thinks she wants. -to not be subject to the EU Court of Justice -which means immigration policy can be set by the UK parliament, but that the UK cannot be in the Customs Union or a member of the EU single market. -She want to have a new and unique deal on trade on goods and services between the UK and EU that gives access to the Single Market. I am not at all sure she understands any of this. Any WTO country can has "access" to the EU single market so no deal is needed, what is important is being a member of the single market. The EU Single Market is a market to guarantee to free movement of Goods and Services, Capital and People, with the EU Court having sovereignty. Mrs May does not want the EU Court or the Free Movement, so presumably what she actually want is a trading deal with EU not the Single Market. This would seem to indicate a deal more similar to that between the EU and South Korea. Most experts on trade negotiations think it (a) unlikely that the EU is keen on the type of deal Mrs May wants (b) even if they are it would be very difficult to get an agreement and ratify it within the 2 year time frame between invoking A59 and Leaving the EU. This is why Ivan Rodgers was reporting that a UK EU deal of this sort would take a long time to sort out. Without repeating the arguments, it is easy sympathize with Ivan Rodgers (EU Ambassador who resigned). Mrs May seems to acting like someone who is sure she knows what she is doing, when those in a position to know are pretty sure she doesn't. (She does not know what she does not know.) People with this outlook tend to do things that are illogical. So she may well trigger A50 in the belief that a deal can be negotiated in 2 years in spite of the various EU elections. The UK Labour Party seems to be completely divided on almost every aspect of Brexit, some don't want any change to the Freedom of movement of people, but would be happy with no trade deal, other want to remain in the Customs Union but accept that the Freedom of Movement needs to be changed. As I noted in a previous forecast this muddle means each time the public are told what Mrs May thinks Bexit means the pound falls, to be followed a day or two later by a statement that the media have confused the markets by not explaining Mrs May's words correctly. The "correction" usually takes the form of saying that remaining in the Customers Union and Single Market have not been ruled out. The only conclusion is that Mrs May does not herself understand what she is saying means.

In the last week or so the EU, David Davis, Liam Fox and Mrs May have all commented on matters that effect this question. The EU has suggested that the 2 year leaving period that starts with A50 is in reality 18 months to negotiate plus 6 months for all parties (the EU, the EU Parliament and the nation states) to ratify and plan to implement. They have also pointed out that ideally the UK needs to have left the EU before the next EU Parliamentary elections due in May 2020. David Davis has pointed out that until the French and German elections are out of the way no substantive negotiations regarding the UK's future relationship with the EU can start. May has repeated her aim to invoke A50 before 31st March. If these 3 sets of dates are taken together we would have A50 by 31st Mar 2017, but no substantive negotiations would start until (probably) the end of September 2017. As the 2 year period would end in February 2019, the negotiations would need to be complete by September 2018 (to give the 6 months to ratify). This seems to show that the period to do the negotiations would be September 2017 to September 2018, which is of course 1 year.

Mrs May still says she will invoke A50 before the end of March, but it now seems that most people expect Parliament will need to approve. There does not seem to have been any rush to get the approval ahead of the Supreme Court judgement that is expected in January (no one is suggesting that it would be wrong to get Parliament's approval regardless of the Supreme Court saying Yes or No). This suggests that (a) Mrs May and the Brexit team are not ready (b) that Mrs May is fully aware that A50 before the French election would force French Presidential candidates to appear more anti-Brexit in order to to seem more Pro-France, which would not help Mrs May. So my conclusion is that Mrs May's plan (if it can be called that) is to hope that "events" give her the excuse to put off A50 until after the French elections and possibly until after the German elections. On the whole the Brexit news seems to be that every weeks brings a new idea of what sort of Brexit is possible, followed a few days later with the reasons why the idea will not works (e.g. today's idea is to pay to keep the existing trade relationship, tomorrow it will be pointed out that to do so will require obeying the European Court of Justice rulings, and accept the free movement of people; both taboos.) In fact any trade deal (CETA, NAFTA, TTIP, WTO) requires some type of court to settle disputes, so its unclear how Brexit can be pro-FreeTrade but against having a dispute settlement body.

British PM was able to secure votes from house of commons that - provided she gives insights as to her plan - supports her March '17 timetable to trigger divorce proceedings with EU [1]. Government will have to wait for appeal result, which is in Jan17. Very little appetite to delay Art50, political pressure to be carrying out Brexit as soon as possible.

The only way the trigger can be delayed is if the government screws it up - for example, by being so vague in describing their plans to Parliament that Parliament refuses to support them. Even in this case, there is enough time by end-June for the two side to sort it out. So I am holding 5 percent for long shots: (i) the SC decides that a very elaborate law is needed; (ii) the government refuses to describe its position to Parliament in meaningful terms and persists in their refusal; (iii) the elaborate law generates such a heated debate that elections are needed; (iv) the economy tanks in 2017:Q1, which gives support to soft Brexiteers, while the government refuses to go soft.

Britain has taken a significant, although largely symbolic, step closer to Brexit after the MPs voted by a majority of almost 400 to back Theresa May’s plan to trigger article 50 by the end of March. Today Britain’s Supreme Court concludes its hearing of the government’s appeal against a High Court judgment that it must secure parliamentary approval before triggering Article 50 of the European Union treaty for Brexit. The justices’ verdict, though, will come only in January. They are expected to rule against the government, obliging it to pass an act of Parliament before invoking Article 50. Such an act must go through both houses, each of which might try to amend it; that may delay the start date beyond the March target set by Theresa May, the prime minister. Mrs May has been trying both to limit parliamentary involvement and to avoid explaining her negotiating goals for Brexit. Now she has promised to publish a plan before invoking Article 50. But do not expect a lot of detail: the plan is unlikely to go much beyond the usual platitudes about getting the best possible deal for Britain

Greg Clerk on the Andrew Marr TV program today said that he had written to Nissan to tell them that the UK would be aiming for a tariff free and free flowing arrangement to allows cars and car parts to go to and from the EU. The only arrangements that appear to match his description would be the EU Customs Unions (on a similar basis to Turkey) or the EU Single Market (like Norway). He also spoke of the need to have similar arrangements for other industries and services. He and May appear to have done a remarkable job of convincing Nissan, that a few weeks previously had said it would not invest in its UK plant without compensation in case tariffs were introduced on Brexit. Bearing in mind that compensation for tariffs is illegal under WTO and EU rules, the UK government seems to be very committed now to the Single Market or the Customs Union. In both cases there exists a more or less standard agreement to sign up to, which it is unlikely that the rest of the EU would object to. But as May and Clerk must be aware both these options preclude the EU making 3rd party trade deals without EU agreement and they both require that the EU Courts enforce the EU set rules. It does not really seem feasible that any agreement like Clerk was describing could operate without a common set of rules and a Court of some kind to deal with disputes. We know the sort of time it takes to create a bespoke trade deal (7 to 10 years seems typical). The UK will (probably) only have two years to do its deal with the EU. So I would suggest that the only possible deal that could be done in 2 years would be to take an existing EU deal such as the Customs Union or Single Market. Maybe with the long term objective of gradually changing it. But in order to do that I am sure that the UK could only get a variation of the Freedom of Movement for Workers and would still need to contribute to the EU budget. The alternative would be no deal at all. Would May be willing to tell Nissan and the motor industry and any other industries that had also been "assured" that there would be no financial or other tariffs that the UK had turned down an offer from the EU for staying in the Customs Union or Single Market? How could the UK "compensate" them? I would not like to be in her shoes if she did not bring a tariff free deal from Brussels. I think "assuring" Nissan that May can deliver has made it impossible not to. And that only an existing agreement can be used in the time frame. That said it would be better to get the uncertainty out of the way and start the process by March. As the issue of immigrants has already blurred into not counting the skilled, graduates, students and vital unskilled workers, it should not be impossible to sort out an acceptable fudge.

If A50 is invoked before the (so called) Great Repeal Bill (actually a consolidation bill that transfers EU law in to British law) there is a legal problem. As I understand it A50 gives a country up to 2 years to complete its negotiations to leave the EU. At the end of the two years EU treaties shall cease to apply to the Leaving country. Therefore it appears to be the case that if the EU invoked A50 in March 2017 all EU Treaties will cease to apply by March 2019 at the latest. I would have thought that if the EU Treaties were just allowed to lapse there would be legal chaos. Hence the need for the Consolidation Law to convert EU law into UK law. But the only way to guarantee that the Consolidation Law is in fact passed before the UK leaves the EU is to pass it before triggering Article 50. Not passing the Consolidation Law before triggering Article 50 appears to be relying on future legislation, which the government may expect to pass, but that there is no way of knowing will pass. Therefore it would appear that in order to protect UK Citizens as well as Citizens of other UK countries legally residing in the UK (who presumably could after March 2017 be classified illegal aliens) A50 has to come after the Consolidation bill. I would assume that many other rights that are provided by EU law would disappear. It does not sound right for the Royal Prerogative (A50) to be used in such a way that Parliament is forced to pass future legislation like it or not. This seems to negate the point of having a Parliament. http://www.lisbon-treaty.org/wcm/the-lisbon-treaty/treaty-on-European-union-and-comments/title-6-final-provisions/137-article-50.html https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/oct/15/new-alliances-oppose-hard-brexit

Theresa May has said that Parliament will debate negotiations over Brexit, but ruled out a vote on Article 50 of the European Union treaty, the legal route to withdrawal. Today a High Court case opens in which the plaintiffs argue that, since Article 50 sets a two-year deadline, invoking it could in effect automatically abrogate the 1972 European Communities Act. That would breach the principle that one parliamentary act can be repealed only by another. The government says the royal prerogative gives it sole rights over foreign policy. The Supreme Court will hear the case in December. Whatever the outcome, demands for greater parliamentary control over Brexit will grow. Britons narrowly voted in June to leave the EU, but they were not told it would mean a “hard” Brexit: walking away from the EU’s single market at huge cost to the economy. On Tuesday, the pound traded around its lowest level on record

After Mrs May announced that A50 would in 2017 before the end of March, she made other comments that made it clear that as far as she was concerned the UK would be heading for "hard Brexit". This has spooked the currency markets and most of the business community (especially that part that trades in Europe). Other statement made at the Conservative Party Conference have indicated that the government appears to be trying to change the direction of the Conservative Party. The cumulative effects have penned up cracks between the views of the government and some Conservative MPs. Coupled with this Labour has appointed Keir Starmer as the Shadow Brexit Minister. These developments appear to be adding impetus the idea that Mrs May cannot be left to dictate the UK's objectives as to what type of Brexit the UK wants and then to lead the negotiations with the EU with the public and MPs denied any input or veto on what the final deal entails. Today several political commentators have expressed doubts that Mrs May's tactics are sustainable. Starmer talked of raising the matter in Parliament. Given that the government has a majority of only 12 it is possible that parliament could demand its say and delay May's timetable. May seems vulnerable as she has also raised policies not directly linked to Brexit, that while popular with party members were not party policy and that are not popular with all her MPs (e.g. Grammar Schools, reporting how many foreigners are employed by each company). She has had her 100 days of honeymoon. It will now be business as usual trying to get all her MPs to follow her when they are not at all happy that they want to go there. If she adds more contentious issues to the mix, such as where to build a new runway for a London airport she could see her hold on the party slip. Once an MP gets into the habit of disagreeing with their party leader its difficult to hold them back.

Europe's responses to potentially invoking Article 50 in early 2017 will give Britain enough excuse to defer the date past June, and increase stability in a post-Brexit world for Britain and arguably also for Europe. Europe will not have a realistic choice to turn its back on Britain simply because of the deferral of 'a few months'.

Two developments; first the announcement that a repeal of the 1972 European Communities Act will be sent to parliament in the next session; second announcement is that article 50 will be invoked between 1 Jan and 31 Mar 2017. However what politicians say will happen and what actually happens is not necessarily the same. Clearly there is pressure on Mrs May to show that progress is being made on Brexit. In my opinion these announcements are more to do with giving the appearance of progress than actually making progress. They relieve the pressure. There is no urgency to repeal the 1972 Act as Mrs May has said it will not be operative until the UK actually leaves the EU, which if A50 is invoked in early 2017 would not be until early 2019. There are several things that could (conveniently) delay the time table. It is not obvious that it would be easy to get the repeal act through parliament. The Conservatives have a small majority in the Commons and no majority in the Lords. It could be that MPs (or Lords) will want more control over the terms of any Brexit deal and will not want to pass the repeal act without knowing what the Brexit terms will be or having a parliamentary vote on triggering A50 or the final Brexit deal. A delay to the repeal act could be used as a reason for delaying invoking A50. It remains odd deciding to invoke A50 a few weeks before a French Presidential election when the candidates for that election have already started to come up with widely different ideas about the kind of deal they would offer the UK. (It is the members of the EU that tell the UK what the terms of Brexit will be). Another reason for delay of A50 could be that Davis has not got his act together by next March and is not ready. Note; Mrs May can blame Davis and his team. On the other hand the motor industry and the banks will be increasingly actioning contingency plans regarding relocating their businesses but repealing the 1972 act and invoking A50 will not actually make the terms of Brexit any clearer, so presumably they will continue with their plans regardless until the actual terms of Brexit are agreed. So I have modified my forecast, but I take what Mrs May says with a pinch of salt.

After 3 months the only Brexit progress is that the people given the job of making it happen are starting to see the logistic problems that they should have recognised before the referendum. e.g. you can't negotiate trade deals while in the EU (or EEA); the UK does not have trade negotiators; 2 years (the time after A50) is not long enough to negotiate a unique trade deal with the EU that will allow key businesses like banks and car makers to have complete access to the single market, Businesses have a duty to their shareholders (not the government) to start moving from the UK if staying could damage their prospects; whatever German car companies might want they don't vote, and the Visegrad countries are not going to agree to protect German car exports if they lose the free movement of their workers into the UK; having an open border between Eire and Northern Ireland creates a big hole in the border of the EU; in spite of the UK enthusiasm for freetrade other countries including the USA seems to heading in the opposite direction (you can be a freetrade unilateralist but the wholesale changes to employment would make Margaret Thatcher's industrial policy seem like a picnic in the park). Its seems that the banks estimate that it will take them at least 4 years to build the new office blocks they will need inside the EU so that they can move without losing business, so they are looking for an interim deal that will give them access to the EU until they can move. Car makers have a much bigger problem in that you can't move a car plant as easily as you can move a desk, but they will not want to have to write off the newer car plants. (My guess is that GM will use Brexit as an excuse to abandon UK manufacturing), the others will want a deal that gives them access to the EU, which means that some sort of deal on retaining at least some of the freedom of movement is needed. The benefits of having immigrants is slowly being recognised; do the Brexit people really believe that redundant bankers and car workers will take over emptying bed pans in care homes, and picking vegetables in Boston? As the months go by a choice between a slow decline as businesses relocate or stay but stop investing because of the uncertainty and A50 with no deal with the EU being in prospect which will produce a fast decline at the end of 2 years. Neither option seems good, so it will be clearer that either a deal to stretch Brexit out over a decade or so, or a decision that Brexit will be abandoned will become desirable.

The procedure required to invoke Article 50 is an unsettled question under UK law and is now the subject of a number of lawsuits. The Plaintiffs who are suing argue that they will lose rights and privileges protected by UK statutes upon the triggering of Article 50 and only Parliament has the power to revoke those rights through legislation. The Prime Minister (PM) says she can invoke under a concept known as the royal prerogative. The royal prerogative is not well defined by law, even though it is the basis for much of the PM’s power to conduct foreign affairs. The Courts hearing the cases will decide if the royal prerogative standing alone is enough under UK law or whether Parliament must pass legislation before Article 50 can be invoked.

Despite Davis declaring Article 50 should be invoked by year end, there are a lot of reasons to think the invocation could be delayed fairly substantially. The referendum isn't binding, and the numbers in parliament are fairly strongly against a Brexit. So it is possible that A50 is never invoked, though it is likely many MPs will go with the judgment of the people. The legal issues here are also quite complex and could bog down (or impede altogether) the invocation of A50. For example, some scholars/legal experts think the Parliament must repeal the 1972 European Communities Act in order to invoke Article 50.
